===Etymology===
{{OE.}} ''[[broþor|brōþor]]'', from Germanic ''*brōþēr'', from Indo-European ''*bʰrāter-''.  Cognates include Dutch ''[[broeder]]'', German ''[[Bruder]]'', and Swedish ''[[broder]]'', all from the same Germanic root; and from Indo-European, Latin ''[[frater]]'', Russian ''[[брат]]'' (brat), Greek ''[[φράτηρ]]'' (frater), Latvian ''[[brãlis]]'', Old Prussian ''[[brāti]]'', and Welsh ''[[brawd]]''.

